  "paragraphs": [
    "While liberties are taken with some of the gods and their relationships, Zelazny uses homages to classical mythology, such as the protagonist Wakim being dismembered limb by limb in a manner similar to Osiris, and the conflict between Horus and Set mirroring the various contests between the two gods in Egyptian sources. The Egyptian gods' ambiguity in their myths enables Robert Zelazny to creatively reinterpret and modify their representations, remaining faithful to their original essence. Osiris sends his son Horus, while Anubis relies on a man named Wakim, who is later revealed to be the destroyer Set, in addition to being Thoth's father.",
    "Zelazny's primary focus lies in ancient Egyptian religion. He occasionally explores Greek mythology, introducing Typhon as the brother of his Egyptian equivalent, Set. \"Roger Zelazny unifies this mythological mix by using binary code, suggesting that all life boils down to the interaction of zero and one. This idea resonates with all mythologies, as they often explore the concept of infinity and the afterlife.\" Infinity's theoretical existence is a common theme in science fiction, fantasy, and academic research. What makes Egyptian mythology so useful in conceiving of a universe where life and death are both fluid and infinite is its concept of the afterlife and the care of the dead.",
    "Osiris and Isis are the most well-known examples of this pairing, with Isis often depicted as both the wife and sister of Osiris. Such an example highlights the ambiguity of the relationships between the gods, as different versions of the same myth can confuse modern interpreters. As noted by Jane Lindskold, one common pitfall when writing immortal characters is that there is little sense of how they perceive time. As a result, their immortality often feels superficial. Zelazny's immortals in \"Creatures of Light and Darkness\" often have unique and contradictory relationships with both time and space, which are closely tied to their ability to comprehend a sense of infinity. While its predecessor, Lord of Light (1967), explored similar themes of technological advancement and traditional mythology, it did so through a novel.",
    "It wasn't until Chip Delany brought it up with an editor that the book would finally be published, bringing joy and puzzlement to its readers. Creatures' oddness is also in part due to its parodying of the New Wave movement, a science fiction subgenre in which Zelazny was considered one of the leading authors. The New Wave was seen as a rejection of pulp-style science fiction, in favor of seemingly more cerebral and complex narratives. Zelazny distanced himself from the term \"New Wave,\" but deemed it \"just a popular tag slapped on a number of writers.\" The creatures in his work seem to be a satirical take on the movement. This parody still retains power, as its shifting of different styles also embodies the distinct representations of the gods, as in both oral and written traditions. Osiris is often associated with eternal life, but this concept is not supported by scientific evidence. While ancient Egyptian mythology portrays Osiris as a god who could grant immortality, there is no credible scientific basis for such claims. Anubis, the god of mummification, oversaw the process for various characters.",
    "It's ironic that Set plays a key role in Osiris's mutilation in some versions of his myth. Osiris's bodily pieces were still considered perfect in this myth and thus able to be reassembled to restore the whole. In contrast, Wakim's body was irreparably damaged in Zelazny's text, a deliberate choice to separate him from his true identity. If Osiris's parts were beautiful, then 7 was a fitting number for his resurrection. Plutarch, Moralia, Volume I Killing someone by beheading or dismemberment was believed to restrict their power in the afterlife.",
    "You had named two things, however. ” “Did I Anubis asked. “Really It doesn't necessarily mean that just because I've used two words, I'm naming two separate and distinct things. The transitory nature of the body is symbolized by the House of the Dead, which is inhabited by living corpses, at the mercy of Anubis. In contrast, the House of the Living is home to living beings undergoing a process of repair and rebirth in preparation for reincarnation.",
    "Existence becomes a matter of controversy. Anubis complicates matters further by introducing the idea that sleep and existence are a paradox. \"A moment ago,\" he says, \"you said that sleep and death were two different things.\" Thoth becomes a superior ruler, enabling him to play a more significant role in governing the universe. He strives to prevent further misuse of power by the other gods.",
    "In the traditional myths, Set and Isis are not depicted as lovers. However, there are instances of seduction between the two, such as when Isis disguises herself as a beautiful woman to distract Set during his competition with Horus. This event may have inspired the reimagined relationship between Set and Isis in Zelazny's text. Set's relationship with Thoth is unusual, as they exist in a strange temporal state. This allows Set to be both father and son to Thoth, a concept that defies Egyptian mythology. Set was rendered feral, forced to seek out conflict in order to survive. His father, Thoth, took on a caretaker role, creating artificial conflicts to sustain him and prevent his own demise until the next crisis arose. Anubis had previously described the concept of life and death in the novel. It was in the section set in Blis that these mechanisms were fully revealed.",
    "The gods reside on Blis, as mortals and immortals blend together. Megra, who had successfully cared for herself for 18 years, now felt it was time to contribute to society. The pursuit of Wakim nearly dooms Megra. As a result, Isis imprisons her, fueled by jealousy. Megra is presented as being much closer to Wakim than Megara was to Hercules, wielding great strength herself, and actively pursuing him.",
    "She even rejects him in favor of Horus by the novel's end, enduring despite the trauma inflicted on her by Isis. The mechanical oracle, meanwhile, is a \"sexcomp\": a computer powered by a human that requires sex to provide answers. Man, the presumptuous organ, has therefore achieved his apotheosis or union with the Gaskethead through sacrifice and redemption, as it were.",
    "While machines can calculate and process data, it's clear that human bodies are necessary to provide the data or memory. Additionally, these oracles are often used for romantic inquiries, leading to a constant exchange of romantic ideas during this transaction. He visits a species known as the Norns, named after Norse deities who shape human fate, and had previously commissioned three of them to build him a replica of a weapon belonging to Set.",
    "After a time, their bodies reject them. Aegyptiaca (2024) Roger Zelazny’s Creatures of Light and Darkness\n\n\"Why is that?\" \"I believe it is because they boast about being able to see among all their people, when in fact they cannot see or foretell the future. They assist Thoth in restoring balance to the universe through their creations.\"",
    "The Norns, derived from Norse mythology, evoke the Fates of Greek and Roman mythology, who share a single eye. This mythological blend by Zelazny renders the Norns as one of the text's chimera. He appears on page 45 of \"Creatures of Light and Darkness\" by Roger Zelazny. Plutarch, Moralia, Volume 1 The first black hole, Cygnus X-1, was discovered in 1964. Despite being a largely theoretical concept at the time the novel was written, the basic function of the black hole - appearing as an empty space from which nothing can escape - is commented on.",
    "\"This is best seen in Typhon sacrificing himself to save Set, consumed by his own power. According to Anubis, \"Skagganauk Abyss\" - also known as the chasm in the sky - is the place where all things stop and nothing else exists.\" \"There are many very empty spaces in the universe.\" \"The abyss has the power to remove objects from reality, particularly outside of the binary paradox of existence. This is why Typhon is considered the most feared of the gods.\" Byram Bowyer, Chubb, and Friedman, \"Cosmic X-ray Sources\" Set was complete at the end of the narrative, but he was not much different from Wakim, despite being more destructive. While Set has accomplished much, it is Thoth who drives the narrative forward with his actions and presence.",
    "Horus is often depicted as Set's arch-nemesis and equal, but it is actually Thoth who better fulfills the role of Set's foil. As a peacekeeper, Thoth serves as a contrast to Set's violent nature. Thoth serves as a mediator within the text, attempting to destroy the Thing That Cries In The Night. He also seeks revenge against his father/son Set by killing Osiris and Anubis, echoing his role as a mediator in the \"Contendings of Horus and Set\". His sections are thoughtful, often marked by poetry. This coincides with his status as a god of wisdom: You did not approve because my father Set, the mightiest warrior who ever lived, was also our son in those days gone by. He was our son during those days in Marachek, after I had broken the temporal barrier to live once again through all time, seeking the wisdom that is past.",
    "Thoth's body does not suffer, nor is he subject to the cycle of life and death. As a result, he is considered the second most powerful deity in the narrative, surpassing only Set. For all his strength, however, there is one thing that Thoth cannot control: the fate of his wife, Nephthys. She no longer has a physical body and has been reduced to a formless entity. The entity occupies a planet whose ocean serves as its atmosphere, evoking the figure of Nun from Egyptian mythology, who is associated with the primeval waters.",
    "The two represent escape and imprisonment from the binary code of the universe. Thoth is free to move about the universe, yet bound by his mission. His wife, on the other hand, is trapped in a state of undeath, but unencumbered by the endless politicking and backstabbing of her family. While it may have been intended as a parody of the New Wave, Zelazny's work instead creates what could be the most intrinsically New Wave novel of all time.",
    "Myths are compatible with scientific concepts like binary code. The reason Egyptian mythology works so well here is that it presents a multifaceted approach to the binary of life and death, thus enabling the exploration of fractal perspectives in Egyptian mythology. While the binary is presented in high terms, such as various pairings of gods and universe-shattering events, it is also presented on smaller and more individual levels, concerning the body and the soul."
